{<b>Bidding. </b>Holding 13 points (10 high-cad points plus three length points) East
opens 1\S. West's 3NT response in standard bidding shows 15–17 high-card
points, no five-card suit, with a doubleton in opener's suit. Opener knows
there is an eight-card fit in spades, but bids diamonds because slam is
possible.

Knowing that East holds spades and diamonds, West knows that the value of his
secondary honors in other suits is diminished greatly. The \HK and \CK J will
likely be of little value to East. West shows a doubleton spade honor by
bidding 4\S. East has bid strongly enough, and passes.

<b>Defense. </b>South leads \HQ, highest of a solid sequence. Unless the \HK is
played, North encourages with the \H9 for South to continue with the \HJ. A
trump lead also has merit, aiming to cut down on diamond ruffs in dummy.

<b>Declarer play. </b>Declarer (East) sees that 4\S is quite high enough. There are
six sure winners. Spades can provide three or four additional winners by
finessing and length, and diamonds may provide two more length winners.

The opening lead marks North with the \HA, so declarer ducks the opening lead
in dummy and ruffs the heart continuation.

There is nothing more important to do than tackle trumps. Declarer finesses in
spades, leading a low spade from hand and playing the \SQ from dummy (unless
South plays the king). This loses to North, who will find continuing with the
\SJ the most attractive option. Declarer wins the \SA and starts on diamonds,
leaving the high trump outstanding.

The best way to tackle diamonds is to play the \DA then the \DK, which might
reveal that North started with \DJ x x x and now can be finessed. The second
round of diamonds actually reveals the bad break the other way. Is nothing
falling declarer's way? Needing one more trick, but unable to afford conceding
a diamond to get a length trick, declarer may consider finessing in clubs. <i>Is
there a better</i> <i>option?</i>

A better plan is to first lead a spade. North has to win this, and will have
the unhappy choice of leading a low heart or a club into dummy, or the \HA
which declarer can ruff, promoting the \HK in dummy. North is <i>endplayed</i>, as
long as declarer didn't squander the \HK early on.}
