{<b>Bidding. </b>North holds 21 points and opens 2NT. Holding 11 points and five
spades, South responds with 3\H, a <i>Jacoby Transfer</i> to show five spades and to
get opener, the stronger hand, to bid spades since any contract usually will
play better by the stronger hand.

Opener holds excellent spade support and reevaluates as declarer, adding a
point for the doubleton heart. At maximum strength, and more, for his previous
bidding, opener can jump to 4\S, a super-acceptance of responder's transfer
bid.

As dummy, South reevaluates upward by a point for the doubleton club but no
longer counts for length. Still at 11 points, South knows that the combined
points are 32, very close to slam. However, her honors are all useful. There is
not a questionable value in South's hand. This makes South's hand worth more
than 11 points

South opts to move toward slam. She uses the 4NT <i>Blackwood</i> convention to ensure
that the partnership isn't missing two aces before bidding 6\S.

<b>Defense. </b>East has no obvious lead. A safe lead of a small spade probably is
best, keeping in mind that West will hold very little. An attacking lead of a
diamond could work out on some hands, but is risky as it is into a very strong
hand.

<b>Declarer play. </b>On a spade lead, North counts eleven sure winners. The diamond
finesse might provide a twelfth, but South's \D10 9 offer a sure way to make
the slam.

North should pull trump, play \HA-Q, \CA-K and ruff a club, and the \HK,
discarding a diamond from hand. Now, the lead of the \D 10 leaves the defenders
with no recourse. When East wins the \D J, East will either have to lead a
diamond into the A Q, or another suit for declarer to ruff in his hand for his
twelfth trick. East is <i>endplayed</i>. And, if West covers the \D10, declarer will
be able to promote a twelfth trick in diamonds.

Stripping the hand and leading the \D5 to the queen accomplishes the same
endplay. Also note that <u>South</u> cannot make 6\S if West hits upon the lead of a
diamond. Yeah, transfers!}
