{<b>Bidding. </b>After West limits the hand by rebidding 1 NT, new suits by East are
not forcing unless a reverse or jump-shift. East must jump-shift to 3\H to
compel West to bid again.

West holds four hearts, but his holding in East's suits are otherwise abysmal
while his minor-suit holdings are very strong. West should not raise hearts,
but indicate the nature of his hand by rebidding notrump. If West raises
hearts, East will try for slam quicker than you can say “Blackwood,” and the
final contract of 5 \H (missing two aces) will be in jeopardy.

<b>Defense. </b>North starts with the \C10, highest of a solid sequence. Leading
spades, East's suit, would be a poor shot.

<b>Declarer play. </b>Declarer (West) counts six sure winners. Two more can be
promoted in spades, and another two in diamonds. Hearts will provide another if
the \H J falls.

Declarer should win the opening club lead in hand the the \CA or \CK for
maximum flexibility of using clubs as entries later. Declarer next lead a spade
to dummy's king. It is better to lead toward potential winners. When the \SK
wins, declarer leads a diamond to the king in hand, and another spade to
dummy's queen. Now with two spades in the bag, West should try dummy's hearts.
When hearts don't work, West should use clubs to enter the hand twice to get
another trick in diamonds.

West must mind entries to hand. The club opening lead removes one, but winning
the second club with the jack preserves the king to overtake the queen and
provide a third entry.

South has had to discard a heart and a diamond on tricks in spades and clubs.
After securing a second trick in diamonds, declarer actually can endplay South
in diamonds to take eleven tricks in all, losing just two diamonds.}
