{<b>Bidding. </b>South's 2\H response promises five, so North can raise with only
three. Once North raises hearts, South adds four points for shortness (but not
also two for heart length) and knows that North-South are in the slam zone.
However, South's two small diamonds are troubling, and North may hold a hand
unsuitable for slam.

South explores for slam by first bidding clubs to show the ace there. North
deprecates the \SJ and \DQ J, minor honors in side suits, and so has no reason
to go beyond game. South can make one more try for slam by bidding 4\S (5\C or
5 \H also works), which shows a control in spades and puts the focus squarely
on diamonds. However, North cannot control diamonds, and besides is now certain
that the \DQ J are worthless to South. North signs off in 5\H.

<b>Defense. </b>West leads the \DA. Leading an ace without the king is unusual against
a suit contract, but the auction has pinpointed the weakness of North-South in
diamonds. East should encourage with the \D8. After winning the \DK, East
should shift to a club up to weakness to give declarer no help.

South counts 10 sure winners. The eleventh can come from a finesse in spades or
clubs. Better is to try to establish a length trick in spades since it can be
done without risk.

South should win the \CA and start spades immediately by playing the \SA and
ruffing a spade. Then the \HA and a heart to dummy's queen to ruff a second
spade. Noting the even break in spades, South now leads a heart to the ten in
dummy, pulling the defender's last trump, to play \SK and another, discarding
two clubs on these to fulfill the contract.

Note that South needed three entries to dummy — two to ruff spades and one to
take the established spades. Declarer uses the \SA, \HQ and \H10 for the
purpose.}
