{<b>Bidding. </b>East has an awkward rebid after 1\S. East holds insufficient strength
to “reverse” into 2\H, and would like a sixth diamond to rebid 2\D. 1NT, 2\C,
or 2\D are all compromise possibilities. I give the nod to 2\D because the
diamonds are strong while the clubs are weak.

West's 3\C “high reverse” should promise the values for game since it compels
South to bid at the three-level with no certainty of a fit.

After East bids 3NT, West holds quite a nice hand for suit play and makes a try
for slam by belatedly raising diamonds to show support.

East infers that West is short in hearts for having bid the other three suits.
Just as with <i>Jacoby 2NT</i> shortness bids, East's \HK Q are not valuable for slam
purposes so East signs off in notrump. 5\D will make, but notrump scores
better.

<b>Defense. </b>South leads the fourth-best heart, the unbid suit. North should play
the \H 10, third hand high, so that East does not win an undeserved trick with
the \H 9.

<b>Declarer play. </b>Declarer (East) counts eight sure winners and another from the
heart lead. A tenth might come from the spade finesse or club finesse, but
there is a sure way.

Declarer's strong hearts are good enough to promote a second trick there.
Declarer can win the opening heart lead and play another heart. Then, a third
round of hearts will promote a second heart trick.

Declarer will have to navigate a couple of pitfalls. If South wins a heart and
shifts to a spade, declarer should play the \S 9 from dummy, not the \SQ, to
prevent the defenders from developing two spade tricks. Also, East needs two
entries to hand: one to play a third round of hearts and one to take the
established heart. These entries must come from diamonds, so declarer must play
the \D Q from dummy and overtake in his hand (or low to the \D10) to play a
second heart. Later, declarer can take the \D J and three more diamonds to land
the contract.}
