{<b>Bidding. </b>When North responds 1\S, South reassesses as dummy in a spade
contract. South now holds 16 high-card points and four points for the singleton
club. Now in the zone of maximum strength for an opening hand (19–21) points,
South jumps to game in spades.

North reassesses as declarer once spades are raised, but there's no improvement
to North's 11 points. However, every card is pulling its weight — two aces are
sure values, and the \HQ will help fill out South's hearts. North drives to
slam, using 4NT Blackwood to check if two aces are missing before bidding slam.

<b>Defense. </b>East has no clear-cut lead. I would lead a club to try to create a
trick there, but it could cost a trick, too. The lead of a singleton heart in
dummy's first-bid suit leaves me cold, but could work. Leading a trump is
another good shot. Who would guess that a diamond lead makes declarer's life
difficult?

<b>Declarer play. </b>Declarer (North) counts eight sure winners and hopes for two
more from spade length. Two more can come from ruffing clubs in dummy, or
perhaps by establishing heart length. The problem with ruffing clubs is that
the second club must be ruffed with a high spade, which may be needed to pull
trumps. On the other hand, if East has led a heart, this should be read as a
singleton so that West holds five hearts and no extra trick can be developed in
hearts.

It may seem as if North can cash two high spades before ruffing clubs, but
should consider how to return to hand after ruffing the second club. Best is to
cash just one round of spades.

When the \SJ falls, declarer is nearly certain to make. Declarer can ruff both
clubs <i>high</i> in dummy, using the \CA and \DA as entries, then lead the \S7 from
dummy to high trumps and claim.

If North tries to win a second round of hearts before pulling trumps, the
contract may may fail.}
